\s1 The story of Terah’s family  
\p
\v 27 This is \w the|strong="H3205"\w* story about \w Terah|strong="H8646"\w*’s family. \w Terah|strong="H8646"\w* \w had|strong="H3205"\w* 3 \w sons|strong="H3205"\w*, called Abram, \w and|strong="H3205"\w* \w Nahor|strong="H5152"\w*, \w and|strong="H3205"\w* \w Haran|strong="H2039"\w*.  
\p \w Haran|strong="H2039"\w* \w had|strong="H3205"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w son|strong="H3205"\w* called \w Lot|strong="H3876"\w*.  
\v 28-29 And he also had 2 daughters called Milcah and Iscah. After that, Haran died, while his father Terah was still alive. He died in the town called Ur, in Chaldia country, the place where he was born.  
\p Nahor, Haran’s brother, married Milcah. And Abram married \w a|strong="H3068"\w* woman called Sarai,  
\v 30 \w but|strong="H1961"\w* Abram \w and|strong="H1961"\w* \w Sarai|strong="H8297"\w* didn’t \w have|strong="H1961"\w* \w any|strong="H1961"\w* kids. \w Sarai|strong="H8297"\w* just couldn’t \w have|strong="H1961"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* baby.   
\p
